tty.get();\\n 102         }\\n 103 \\n 104         static int connectionAttempts() {\\n-105             return CONNECTION_ATTEMPTS.get();\\n+105             return connectionAttempts.get();\\n 106         }\\n 107 \\n 108         static void deregister() throws SQLException {\\n-109             DriverManager.deregisterDriver(REGISTERED_DRIVER);\\n+109             DriverManager.deregisterDriver(registeredDriver);\\n 110         }\\n 111 \\n 112         @Override\\n 113         public Connection connect(String url, Properties info) throws SQLException {\\n-114             CONNECTION_ATTEMPTS.incrementAndGet();\\n+114             connectionAttempts.incrementAndGet();\\n 115             return null;\\n 116         }\\n 117 \\n 118         @Override\\n     ...\", \"firstChangedLine\": 76}, \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777737074631}]}\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge6/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.eclipse.jetty:jetty-security:9.3.19.v20170502/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-02T15-52-51-875947Z.log:1951:[thinking] I might need a top-level helper class that isn't a test class, which seems like a good direction. The existing `Jetty_securityTest` is more of a generic placeholder and might not be necessary with the dedicated active class. However, I’m wondering if a generic test is causing any one-to-one mapping violations. It’s a bit perplexing!\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge6/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.eclipse.jetty:jetty-security:9.3.19.v20170502/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-02T15-52-51-875947Z.log:1953:[thinking] **Considering test coverage**\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge6/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.eclipse.jetty:jetty-security:9.3.19.v20170502/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-02T15-52-51-875947Z.log:1955:[thinking] I'm thinking about whether I should delete a placeholder test file. It’s not linked to an active class, and while it runs, it lacks coverage. Should I leave it as is since it serves as a placeholder? But, if the idea is to have active class coverage in a dedicated Java test file, maybe it’s not necessary. I should really inspect the git diff to make a more informed decision!\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge6/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.eclipse.jetty:jetty-security:9.3.19.v20170502/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-02T15-52-51-875947Z.log:1961:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating naming and registration issues**\\n\\nI’m considering whether having the same name for methods and fields is legal in Java. It looks like it’s allowed, like with `int size` and `int size()`. I’m also thinking about potential issues with deregistering drivers if they’re already deregistered. \\n\\nIf something fails before the static initialization, it could lead to exceptions that mask test failures. I wonder if it’s better to handle deregistration after connecting. Plus, I have concerns about static initialization possibly triggering issues. It's a lot to manage!\\n\\n**Analyzing class loading and resources**\\n\\nI'm exploring what happens when `.newInstance` initializes and calls the constructor, which seems straightforward. There’s potential concern about resources with `DriverManager` and classloader references, but if tests aren't supposed to compile or run, I can focus on reading instead. \\n\\nI’m questioning whether the dynamic report needs inspection. The problem about “open-ended dynamic class loading” doesn't seem to apply here, since the class is known at image build. It dynamically loads from runtime config, but it’s manageable with metadata, so no need for error catching.\\n\\n**Evaluating metadata generation issues**\\n\\nI'm considering potential issues with metadata generation related to dynamic access reports. It looks like `Class.forName` from `connectDatabase` is included, but since our `TestDriver` class is found, that should be fine. \\n\\nI might need a top-level helper class that isn't a test class, which seems like a good direction. The existing `Jetty_securityTest` is more of a generic placeholder and might not be necessary with the dedicated active class. However, I’m wondering if a generic test is causing any one-to-one mapping violations. It’s a bit perplexing!\\n\\n**Considering test coverage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether I should delete a placeholder test file. It’s not linked to an active class, and while it runs, it lacks coverage. Should I leave it as is since it serves as a placeholder? But, if the idea is to have active class coverage in a dedicated Java test file, maybe it’s not necessary. I should really inspect the git diff to make a more informed decision!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05857f5c7c133a070169f61d73e0e88194ab564f807a5a71ec\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9h2Ak1dixC9Kw665KmTYUJgVm78IL9WpwnepfeYAwh0B214Bjk3uBUMyo7FdrWPQkmOIApPGK2zhsYLQXErXnXIwp_YwRhJ7ksZfE_XMUAzwv72V48Z6LZq9A1UVam8D59j-RvcZqMCHZOZBfe0DmoFbnsK3eylAP11pEd9b58E1OYr0LvHPOkSNjl3nxS9GlvSM_HqO-LimeN9SDNB0FHCmr7i4aU9S11bggC_TzL56z60xbxAH-vKvppQPbFyIqJSLfZYhxqAVRyqF3uDxHzknegQrgE-ATJaJvv0owSpzLDS4sDTtmNvctUZXeYNCOdF5DdzJw5BHoD5QU-e2AlEm3xCI3lW2wPqRqTSlt78VlVms7LyK0ID122EuqeULvtgUlhDG_aO0MH_AywglVJ2pLZI_dAVr7RUl5O7jQSvY939haH9jtNWrraoCwTGuN0kJ9uiFnG4X8y5Umb47azi064OizE_J8ld28ixUy5r8BywuAiQqDHDSwQFTc-CFORKfcKuaA3Ok28ckUlQuUPZrjp_IhWv06t_qHnqlIYwFceLCu6nNc6QJ_U-sns-s47qTSt1mWuHu9pczYRuJM8uWWfAR9WMtSJ4DnuTAA1dXEQPWNPrWKTo8TOq8S1P9tSjsw2gyf3htIGP7ihhE2316rtwFaxJi0iXK1mKhk3qQtHbHzvJnCAKFXbw5kTzmhw9U3Ybk1L4GMVOImM3S8JrqwmdsW2c24w8Fesnn4CChlz1u0duO8uZ0vSVhxWNYJOANLpZ1D4Y7dv5bBBsoiPqUkhGnLT1Kx_zn2p61nqJroj8j5SFHuejj7Szf4OSS4fUIRUtVm9YgwPXab5-aDUdYPkZFgdWB3zkVmt97JT6QNHoUyoDhkB9S2weIUVIERWuLrc6XDvcO7VfhO1l-oYOboDL-K7uQzHqkNAf7Pc4TEVhCA7guyTTeGQFrdfXtfxLj_qeROLiZvYe-phhGQYJsTp-TfwiB7V5T9yu0J28cu90rjrt6uG1-zIV4kNAZ2dVIDEeysRi