ut it’s manageable with metadata, so no need for error catching.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Evaluating metadata generation issues**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm considering potential issues with metadata generation related to dynamic access reports. It looks like `Class.forName` from `connectDatabase` is included, but since our `TestDriver` class is found, that should be fine. \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI might need a top-level helper class that isn't a test class, which seems like a good direction. The existing `Jetty_securityTest` is more of a generic placeholder and might not be necessary with the dedicated active class. However, I’m wondering if a generic test is causing any one-to-one mapping violations. It’s a bit perplexing!\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Considering test coverage**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm thinking about whether I should delete a placeholder test file. It’s not linked to an active class, and while it runs, it lacks coverage. Should I leave it as is since it serves as a placeholder? But, if the idea is to have active class coverage in a dedicated Java test file, maybe it’s not necessary. I should really inspect the git diff to make a more informed decision!\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_ZlRIaxhSh3pkJrlD0cgKT160|fc_05857f5c7c133a070169f61d80705c8194bb0040c53f85d14f\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"bash\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"command\\\": \\\"git status --short && git diff -- tests/src/org.eclipse.jetty/jetty-security/9.3.19.v20170502/src/test/java/org_eclipse_jetty/jetty_security/JDBCLoginServiceTest.java\\\"}}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\": \\\"gpt-5.5\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 933, \\\"output\\\": 653, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 25600, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"totalTokens\\\": 27186, \\\"cost\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 0, \\\"output\\\": 0, \\\"cacheR